The ‘bee car’ that avoids collisions
To advance in the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, specifically, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers from Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Advanced Science and Technology Research Center of the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan’s four-area Security Shield.
This robot is intended to strengthen the collision prevention capability of the brand’s vehicles.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space with an oval shape that is very similar to the Nissan Safety Shield.
But most importantly, the bee’s composite eyes, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly uninterruptedly within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles up to two meters away within a radius of 180 degrees in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to said object and sends a signal to an approach microprocessor that immediately translates into collision prevention.
“As soon as you detect an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by rotating its wheels at a straight or larger angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If it weren’t, the robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be turned upwards or downwards, or diagonally; it can only be moved in two dimensions and in the direction that allow it to rotate its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotational function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, for the small robot to avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act according to that data.
It does not require saving information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we’re not talking about memory gigs, not even mega ones.”
This is the first step in developing new instantaneous collision prevention technologies, a technology Nissan predicts that will be introduced to serial cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a satellite navigation GPS system to guide the driver to their destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
