Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Restoring the Republic around 21st Century Socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, in the example of his colleagues and friends, is the third to put to the vote a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission fulfilled as 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to official results that refer to 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were blank votes.
In order for the draft constitution to be adopted, one more half of the votes had to be obtained.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polling stations and a count on the part of a non-governmental organization had announced a broad victory to the "yes", estimating it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had further claimed on the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft constitution.
The “Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly,” he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who led the government of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chavez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will be held in full calm, according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a 444-point text that consolidated the president-sponsored " new socialism " .
The draft Constitution involves increasing the power of the State over the economy, reserving the " development planning " of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to the currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants reinforced powers to the Head of State, which will be able to hold up to two consecutive four-year mandates each and will have the possibility of disbanding the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and will seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
19 kidnapped people have been released in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by the Egyptian special forces in Chad.
All of them had a good look at their arrival at 3:30 p.m. on board a special plane to the military base of Al Maza, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, to undergo medical tests, so they were unable to speak to the press.
"They are well" and "no rescue was paid" to the kidnappers, said at the airport Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana.
On September 19, these hostages fell into the power of 35 unknown hijackers while enjoying an all-terrain safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since passed from one Zulu to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptus, in charge of the organization of the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, transported on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"A shooting swap occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest have fled," said the official who kept the anonymity.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces were sent to Sudan, where they had the support of German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
“We have to recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our men from the secret services, from the special forces,” he said.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The Sudanese army said it had intercepted an all-terrain patrol on board of which were the hijackers, who killed six, including the Chadian chief and arrested two.
He also claimed that they were related to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), a statement immediately denied by this group.
