Zorro in the Chicken
In the United States, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract when viewing drug purchase data.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the personal data market will become uncontrollable.
“There are programs for the protection of personal data, which in all cases bind the use of prescription data to the approval of the person concerned.
The same should be in independent hands, because otherwise, "we trust the chicken to the fox" - quotes the Washington Post to Richard Dick, designer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the insurance price and the amount of compensation depend on the health status of the customer and if they believe the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Previously, they sent the client to medical check and signed the contract with him knowing the result of the check.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number, pharmacy easily gets the list of drugs purchased in the last year and a half, and the program itself draws conclusions about the patient’s illness and health status.
For example, if you take systematically large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is practically incurably high, so you are immediately included in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a risk number, so the insurance company in addition to the administration has barely anything to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is, for example, that some drugs are multipurpose, for example, certain substances serve both to treat headaches and heatwaves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is an important risk-increasing factor for insurance companies while the first ones are not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which, before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, request the patient's approval.
Authorities are already obliged to do so, although they have not received a fine for negligence so far.
Some companies have recently also elaborated the results of laboratory tests and by combining them with drug consumption data they obtain more accurate information about the patient’s state of health.
More and more companies have access to this data and at the same time it is increasingly difficult to control their use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and those providing health services.
The Congress is already facing the bill that gives the authority to control specialized companies for the provision of personal data.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his program, which will require the specific approval of the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the chickens, however, are exposed to the good will of the fox.
